## 1. Project Overview and Business Objective
The task is to predict whether an SBA-backed small-business loan will default (charge off) versus be paid in full, using application-time features. The business objective is to help a lender flag higher-risk loans before approval so it can price, decline, or add conditions to risky applications. In practice the final model outputs a default probability per loan, and a tuned threshold turns that into an approve/review decision.

## 2. Data Quality Findings
The labeled data has 809,247 rows and 19 modeling columns after dropping the `index` identifier. Missing values appear in `RevLineCr` (~4.1k), `LowDoc` (~2.3k), `BankState`/`Bank` (~1.4k), and a few in `City`, `State`, and `NewExist`. Several categoricals carry inconsistent codes — `RevLineCr` and `LowDoc` contain values like `0`, `T`, `` ` ``, `C`, `S` beyond the expected `Y`/`N`, and `NewExist` has invalid `0` entries. High-cardinality fields include `Bank`, `City`, `NAICS`, `Zip`, `State`, `BankState`, and `FranchiseCode`. The target is imbalanced at ~17.5% defaults (141,881 of 809,247). The `index` column was excluded as an index-like identifier; monetary fields were already numeric, so no string-to-number repair was needed.

## 3. Train/Validation/Test Split Strategy
I split the labeled data 70/15/15 using two stratified `train_test_split` calls (30% holdout, then split in half), stratifying on the target so each split keeps the ~17.5% default rate.

| Split | Purpose | Row count | Positive rate |
| --- | --- | ---: | ---: |
| Train | Fit preprocessing and models | 566,473 | ~17.5% |
| Validation | Tune models and thresholds | 121,387 | ~17.5% |
| Test | Final locked evaluation | 121,387 | ~17.5% |

The Test set was never touched during tuning: all preprocessing objects and models were fit on Train, every hyperparameter and threshold decision was scored on Validation only, and the Test set was loaded once at the very end for the final metrics.

## 4. Preprocessing and Leakage Controls
Missing values are imputed with Train medians for numerics and a `MISSING` category for categoricals; messy `RevLineCr`/`LowDoc`/`NewExist`/`UrbanRural` codes are mapped to clean levels deterministically. Low-cardinality categoricals are one-hot encoded against Train levels (unseen values → all zeros), and high-cardinality categoricals (`Bank`, `City`, `NAICS`, `Zip`, `State`, `BankState`, `FranchiseCode`) use smoothed target encoding. Numerics are standardized (z-scored) using Train means and standard deviations. Every imputer, encoder map, and scaler statistic is fit on Train only and stored in a `preprocessing` dict. Validation, Test, and scoring data are passed through the same `apply_cleaning_and_preprocessing()` transform — which only looks up stored values, never refits — and reindexed to the saved feature order so columns always match.

## 5. Feature Engineering Summary
All 15 engineered features below are derived quantities, not encodings or copies.

| # | Feature name | Formula or logic | Why it may help |
| ---: | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | `sba_guarantee_ratio` | `SBA_Appv / GrAppv` (clipped 0–1) | Higher government guarantee shifts risk off the bank and signals loan structure. |
| 2 | `bank_exposure_amt` | `GrAppv − SBA_Appv` | Dollars the bank itself is exposed to if the loan fails. |
| 3 | `disb_to_appv_ratio` | `DisbursementGross / GrAppv` | Top-ups or under-draws versus the approved amount can signal risk. |
| 4 | `appv_per_employee` | `GrAppv / NoEmp` | Loan leverage per worker; very high values may be over-extended. |
| 5 | `total_jobs` | `CreateJob + RetainedJob` | Overall employment supported by the loan. |
| 6 | `appv_per_job` | `GrAppv / total_jobs` | Capital intensity per job; extremes flag thin justification. |
| 7 | `log_gross_appv` | `log1p(GrAppv)` | Tames heavy right-skew so the linear model reads loan size sensibly. |
| 8 | `log_disbursement` | `log1p(DisbursementGross)` | Same skew correction for disbursed dollars. |
| 9 | `same_state_lender` | `State == BankState` | Local lending may carry better borrower knowledge / lower risk. |
| 10 | `naics_sector` | First 2 digits of `NAICS` | Groups 1,300+ industry codes into broad sectors with shared risk. |
| 11 | `is_franchise` | `FranchiseCode > 1` | Franchises have brand/operational support that can lower default risk. |
| 12 | `appv_size_bucket` | Binned `GrAppv` into 5 ordinal tiers | Captures non-linear size effects on default. |

All engineered features were used in the final model; none were dropped.

