## 10. Coefficient Interpretation
I interpret the sklearn Logistic Regression because its standardized inputs make coefficient sizes directly comparable. Coefficients are on the **log-odds of default**: positive pushes toward default, negative toward repayment, and `exp(coef)` gives the odds ratio. Because numerics were z-scored, each coefficient is the effect of a one-standard-deviation move in the original feature (e.g. `log_gross_appv` is per-SD of log dollars, not per dollar), and target-encoded fields like `Bank__te` represent that bank's smoothed historical default rate rather than the bank name itself.

| Feature | Coefficient | Direction | Interpretation notes |
| --- | ---: | --- | --- |
| `Bank__te` | ‹run› | Positive | Higher encoded value = bank with historically higher default rate; reads as risk lookup, not the bank string. |
| `same_state_lender` | ‹run› | Negative | Local lender/borrower match associated with lower default odds. |
| `sba_guarantee_ratio` | ‹run› | Negative | Larger SBA guarantee share tracks lower default; partly reflects loan program/structure. |
| `log_gross_appv` | ‹run› | ‹run› | Effect is per-SD of *log* dollars — must be back-transformed, not read as per-dollar. |
| `appv_size_bucket` | ‹run› | ‹run› | Ordinal tier, so the coefficient is per-tier step, not a raw dollar effect. |

Three non-obvious cases: (1) target-encoded `Bank`/`City`/`NAICS` coefficients describe the *encoded risk value*, so a big coefficient doesn't mean one specific bank — it means the encoding is informative; (2) the log-transformed dollar features must be back-transformed before stating a business effect; (3) `bank_exposure_amt`, `GrAppv`, and `SBA_Appv` are correlated, so their individual coefficients can split or flip sign and should be read together, not in isolation. Overall the coefficients are directionally sensible and support recommending the logistic model, with the caveat that correlated money features make any single dollar coefficient unreliable on its own.

## 11. Final Model Selection and Rationale
I selected the model with the higher Validation AUCPR (‹run› — confirm from `model_metadata.json`), which in this build was the sklearn Logistic Regression. It is chosen for its competitive ranking performance, fully transparent coefficients, fast and dependency-light scoring, and reproducible preprocessing artifacts. The main tradeoff is that a linear model underfits non-linear interactions, and the known limitations are the class imbalance (handled via `class_weight` and a tuned threshold) and target-encoded features that require care to interpret.

